glioma in the midbrain status post\r\ncyst debulking with multiple surgeries, including tumor\r\ndebulking, suboccipital craniectomy, fenestration of trapped\r\nfourth ventricle, endoscopic third ventriculostomy. Follow for\r\nchange. Low grade glioma -  Malignant neoplasm of cerebellum\r\n\r\n\r\nTECHNIQUE: Sagittal T1 MPRAGE with axial reformations, axial and\r\nsagittal TSE T2, axial and coronal FLAIR, axial spin echo T1,\r\narterial spin labeled perfusion imaging, post-contrast T1\r\nsagittal MPRAGE with axial and coronal reformations,\r\npost-contrast axial spin echo T1, and axial diffusion imaging\r\nwere performed on a 3.0 Tesla system.\r\n\r\n\r\nCOMPARISON:  Multiple prior studies including the first baseline\r\nMRI brain May 28, 2018 and most recent MRI brain January 02, 2025\r\n\r\n\r\nFINDINGS:\r\nStatus post suboccipital craniotomy with susceptibility foci and\r\nsoft tissue retraction in the surgical site redemonstrated. There\r\nis interval resolution of the small pseudomeningocele noted in\r\nthe surgical site.\r\n\r\n\r\nThe is interval improvement of the previously seen dilated,\r\ncystic-like configuration of the fourth ventricle with internal\r\nseptation/adhesion which has now decreased in size with interval\r\nseemingly free communication between the enlarged fourth\r\nventricle and the infra cerebellar cistern and noting interval\r\nflow void traversing between both CSF spaces. Persistent marked\r\nfourth ventriculomegaly is present, but again less pronounced\r\ncompared to the prior study. The anterior posterior dimension\r\nmeasures 2.6 cm compared to 4.0 cm from prior study dated\r\n01/02/2025. Additionally, there is interval less mass effect upon\r\nthe cerebellum and brainstem. \r\n\r\n\r\nPersistent adhesion located in the distal cerebral aqueduct\r\ndistorting the midbrain tegmentum, reaches current less distorted\r\nhowever still obliterating the cerebral aqueduct. The brainstem\r\nis interval which nearly anatomical configuration, occupying the\r\nanterior half of the posterior fossa, with additional interval\r\nopening of the ventral prepontine and premedullary cisterns with\r\ninterval better visualization of the course and flow void of the\r\nbasilar artery. \r\n\r\n\r\nStable supratentorial ventricle size with each is noted mild to\r\nmoderate prominent, unchanged. Patent third ventriculostomy with\r\nCSF flow noted traversing the osteotomy defect towards the\r\nprepontine cistern. Moderate third ventriculomegaly is also\r\nunchanged.\r\n\r\n\r\nStable changes prior left parietal craniotomy, with associated\r\nparietal surgical cavity and peripheral gliosis. Stable prior\r\nright frontal catheter tracts with surrounding\r\nencephalomalacia/gliosis.\r\n\r\n\r\nRedemonstration of the surgical site from previous resection of\r\ncomplex cystic appearing lesion, with stable postsurgical\r\nsusceptibility artifacts involving the left superior cerebellar\r\npeduncle and resection of the leftward posterolateral medulla and\r\npons and lateral margin of the fourth ventricle. Redemonstration\r\nof the mild dural thickening/enhancement along the left tentorium\r\nleaflet which appears slightly more prominent, with axial\r\nthickening of 7 mm compared to 5 mm.\r\n\r\n\r\nPostsurgical changes with less conspicuous enhancement in the\r\nregion of the left sided midbrain and dorsal thalamus, (series 17\r\nframe 49-50, please compare with series 17 image 50 from prior\r\nstudy of 12/2/2024). Please note that the immediate prior study\r\nwas performed without contrast, therefore comparison with the\r\nsecond most recent study was performed.\r\n\r\n\r\nStable scattered foci of enhancement in the left dorsal thalamus\r\n(series 17 frame 49) and left superior cerebellar peduncle\r\n(series 17 frame 54), not significantly changed overall.\r\n\r\n\r\nRedemonstration of the underlying T2 prolongation in the surgical\r\nsite, most notably involving the left dorsal thalamus and left\r\nsided midbrain along with the left superior cerebellar peduncle,\r\ngrossly unchanged. There is interval improvement of the T2\r\nprolongation surrounding the fourth ventricle and the cerebellar\r\nwhite matter. Overall, stable chronic volume loss cerebellum,\r\nleft greater than right. \r\n\r\n\r\nPersistent mild thinning corpus callosum.\r\n\r\n\r\nNo definite change in appearance major intracranial vessels.\r\n\r\n\r\nNo definite abnormality visualized orbits. \r\n\r\n\r\nSubtle hyperintense T2 signal within the left mastoid air cells\r\nmight reflect mucosal thickening or fluid retention. Otherwise,\r\nright mastoid air cells and middle ear cavities, and paranasal\r\nsinuses are clear. hx of brain tumor, surgical planning for ventricular fenestration, stealth, sagittal fiesta\r\n\r\n\r\nEXAMINATION: \u00a0MR BRAIN W AND WO CONTRAST, 2/13/2025 4:41 PM, MR25020132227\r\n\r\n\r\nCOMPARISON: MRI brain with and without contrast, 9/26/2024 and 9/27/2024; CT head without contrast, 02/13/2025.\r\n\r\n\r\nTECHNIQUE: \u00a0Axial thin section contiguous T2-weighted imaging of the brain without intravenous contrast was performed per stealth protocol. \u00a0Axial diffusion tensor imaging, axial T2-weighted imaging, axial SWAN imaging, sagittal cube T2, 3-D sagittal FIESTA, coronal STIR imaging, and axial diffusion-weighted imaging with ADC mapping was performed. \u00a0Prior to and after the uneventful administration of 12 mL Multihance intravenous contrast, axially acquired volumetric gradient T1 weighted imaging of the brain was performed per stealth protocol. \u00a0Pre and postcontrast sagittal cube FLAIR images were also obtained.\r\n\r\n\r\nFINDINGS: \r\nThere is an infiltrative T2 hyperintense mass centered at the posterior aspect of the left cerebral peduncle, with extension to the thalamus, measuring the area of signal abnormality at least 1.2 x 1.6 x 0.9 cm (measured craniocaudal by anteroposterior by transverse dimension on series 10 image 23 and series 7 image 42). \u00a0There is corresponding FLAIR hyperintense signal, T1 hypointensity, and not enhancement. \u00a0There is facilitated diffusion. \u00a0Posterior and lateral to the infiltrative tumor within the left ambient cistern there is thick enhancement surrounding the left vein of Rosenthal (series 11 image 68) measuring approximately 0.7 x 0.9 x 0.6 cm (series 11 image 68). \u00a0Posteromedial to the area of the tumor, there are extensive postsurgical changes, extending to the left lateral ventricle trigone, with multiple areas of signal loss on susceptibility images, compatible with hemosiderin deposition. \r\n\r\n\r\nThere is a obliquely oriented thick membrane at the sylvian aqueduct, that demonstrates signal loss susceptibility images (series 801 image 115). \u00a0Below this membrane there is a 2nd membrane that appears to represent a cystic entrapment of the 4th ventricle, that is severely dilated, significantly increased in size when compared to prior examination, causing severe mass effect over the adjacent brain stem and cerebellum, causing narrowing of the prepontine and premedullary cisterns. \u00a0Along the inferior margin of the 4th ventricle there are also multiple membranes at the expected location of the 4 ventricular outflow (series 15 image 119), with corresponding signal loss susceptibility images (series 301 image 101). \u00a0Within the cystic dilatation of the 4th ventricle itself there is a prominent septi posterior left laterally (series 15 image 118 and series 7 image 30), that also demonstrate signal loss on susceptibility images. \u00a0There is increased T2/FLAIR hyperintense signal surrounding \r\nthe 4th ventricle (for example series 7 image 25), suggestive of interstitial edema.\r\n\r\n\r\nThere are surgical changes of prior midline occipital craniotomy, with encephalomalacia along the residual vermis. \u00a0There is volume loss of the residual cerebellum. \u00a0There is abnormal FLAIR signal at the midline of the mesencephalon, as well as involving the tectal plate (series 2 image 118).\r\n\r\n\r\nIMPRESSION: \r\n1. \u00a0There are post surgical changes of prior occipital craniotomy for resection of a mass. \u00a0There is remonstration of infiltrative tumor centered at the posterior aspect of the left cerebral peduncle with extension to the thalamus, as well as nonspecific enhancement surrounding the left vein of Rosenthal, approximately stable when compared to intraoperative MRI dated 09/27/2024.\r\n2. \u00a0There is severe cystic dilatation of the 4th ventricle, now with surrounding interstitial edema, significantly increased compared to prior MRI. \u00a0There is a membrane superiorly just below the sylvian aqueduct, as well as a membrane inferiorly at the 4 ventricular outflow; there is a septum at the posterior left aspect of the 4th ventricle. \u00a0Within the sylvian aqueduct there is an obliquely oriented thick membrane. \u00a0The described membranes demonstrate signal loss susceptibility images, likely representing hemosiderin deposition from blood products.\r\n3. \u00a0There are areas of abnormal signal suggestive of gliosis/encephalomalacia involving the mesencephalon, tectal plate, and cerebellum. \u00a0There are extensive postsurgical changes at the left ambient cistern, and extending to the left lateral ventricle trigone.\r\n\r\n\r\nThe images were reviewed with Dr. Klimo from the LeBonheur neurosurgery department at 8:00 PM on 02/13/2025.\r\n\r\n\r\nCOMMENTS: I have reviewed the images and agree with the final report above performed by Deepti V Kathiria. \r\nThis report was 19-year-old female with history of pilocytic astrocytoma. \r\n\r\n\r\nEXAMINATION: \u00a0CT HEAD WO IV CONTRAST, 2/13/2025 4:41 PM, CT25020133456\r\n\r\n\r\nCOMPARISON: Head CT dated 09/28/2024.\r\n\r\n\r\nTECHNIQUE: Helically acquired unenhanced CT images of the head were obtained from the foramen magnum to the vertex. Three plane bone and soft tissue reconstructions were created from the source data. Axial thin section soft tissue reconstructions were created from the source data per Stealth protocol.\r\n\r\n\r\nFINDINGS:\r\nThe pneumocephalus seen on the prior exam has resolved. \u00a0Area of encephalomalacia in the left parietal lobe is similar. \u00a0Compared to the prior CT the lateral ventricles are mildly increased in size at the frontal horns however the posterior and temporal horns do not appear increased. \u00a0Mild increased dilation of the 3rd ventricle. \u00a0Increased dilation of the 4th ventricle with mild surrounding hypoattenuation in the adjacent parenchyma in the left cerebellum. \u00a0Focal calcification in the right temporal horn.\r\n\r\n\r\nNo extra-axial fluid collection. \u00a0Mild heterogeneity of the left thalamus/midbrain which will be better evaluated on contemporaneously performed MRI.\r\n\r\n\r\nNo midline shift. \u00a0Basal cisterns are preserved.\r\n\r\n\r\nParanasal sinuses and mastoid air cells are clear. \u00a0Orbits are unremarkable. \u00a0Prior craniotomies are noted.\r\n\r\n\r\nIMPRESSION:\r\n1. \u00a0Preoperative planning CT.\r\n2. \u00a0Compared to the prior CT scanner from September there is increased dilation of the frontal horns, 3rd ventricle, and 4th ventricle.\r\n\r\n\r\nAll CT scans at this facility use dose modulation, iterative reconstruction, and/or weight based dosing when appropriate to reduce radiation dose to Since prior MRI of 9/9/2024, there is new interval surgical\r\nchange, with evidence for interval resection of previously\r\ndepicted complex cystic appearing lesions abutting the left\r\nsuperior cerebellar peduncle, left parasagittal cystic component\r\nalong the posterolateral medulla and pons extending along the\r\nleft lateral margin of the fourth ventricle, and the dorsal\r\nmidline component along the posterior margin of the third\r\nventricle has been largely resected. \r\n\r\n\r\n2.  There is otherwise persistent cystic/solid signal alteration\r\nwithin the left midbrain with some extension of signal alteration\r\ninto the superior cerebellar peduncle and pons, and within the\r\nleft posterior thalamus, with variable enhancement, as described\r\nabove. \r\n\r\n\r\n3. Prominent ex vacuo dilatation of the fourth ventricle,\r\nincreased in size in the interim measuring 4.2 cm (AP),\r\nconcerning for an element of ventricular entrapment. There is\r\nnew/increased FLAIR signal hyperintensity within the parenchyma\r\nalong the margins of the fourth ventricle which could represent\r\nperiventricular interstitial edema. There is new/increased mass\r\neffect upon the brainstem which is ventrally displaced. \r\n\r\n\r\n4.  There is persistent obliteration of the aqueduct of Sylvius. \r\nThe mildly prominent third ventricle may be slightly smaller in\r\nsize. Otherwise, lateral ventricles are mildly prominent and\r\nsimilar in size.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nRESULTS NOTIFICATION:\r\nThe findings were communicated to and acknowledged by Dr. JANE\r\nMINTURN via Epic secure chat by Dr. Marlene Baumann on 12/2/2024\r\n11:36 AM.\r\n\r\n\r\nResults Notification: Other Category, see above.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nRequires Act 112 notification: False\r\nAct 112^False","interpretation":NaN,"note":NaN}},{"resource":{"resourceType":"Observation","id":"fv5FcrZGgv3IAekZNB1vpDg4","status":"final","category":"[{id=null, extension=null, coding=[{id=null, extension=null, system=http://terminology.hl7.org/CodeSystem/observation-category, _system=null, version=null, _version=null, code=imaging, _code=null, display=Imaging, _display=null, userSelected=null, _userSelected=null}], text=Imaging, _text=null}, {id=null, extension=null, coding=[{id=null, extension=null, system=urn:oid:1.2.840.114350.1.13.20.2.7.10.798268.30, _system=null, version=null, _version=null, code=Imaging, _code=null, display=Imaging, _display=null, userSelected=null, _userSelected=null}], text=Imaging, _text=null}]","code":"{id=null, extension=null, coding=null, text=Narrative, _text=null}","subject":"{id=null, extension=null, reference=Patient/e4BwD8ZYDBccepXcJ.Ilo3w3, _reference=null, type=null, _type=null, identifier=null, display=Massari, Abigail, _display=null}","effectiveDateTime":"2024-12-02T15:21:01Z","valueQuantity":NaN,"valueString":"\r\n\r\nBRAIN MRI, WITHOUT AND WITH CONTRAST:\r\n\r\n\r\nCLINICAL INDICATION: midbrain low grade glioma -  Compression of\r\nbrain\r\n\r\n\r\nPer electronic medical record, 19 year old with history of\r\nposterior fossa pilocytic astrocytoma s/p resection on 5/28/18. \r\nHer course was complicated by obstructive hydrocephalus and\r\nposterior fossa syndrome. She was admitted to inpatient rehab\r\nfrom 6/14/18-7/20/18. She completed chemotherapy 5/2020.  She is\r\ns/p admission March 2021 for second tumor debulking and therapy\r\nwith Selumetinib. More recently she is status post resection of\r\ncystic tumor with small portion remaining in brainstem in\r\nSeptember 2024.\r\n\r\n\r\nTECHNIQUE: Sagittal T1 MP RAGE with axial and coronal\r\nreformations, axial and sagittal TSE T2, axial and coronal FLAIR,\r\naxial spin echo T1, arterial spin labeled perfusion imaging,\r\npost-contrast T1 sagittal MP RAGE with axial and coronal\r\nreformations, post-contrast axial spin echo T1, and axial\r\ndiffusion imaging were performed on a 3.0 Tesla system.\r\n\r\n\r\nCOMPARISON:  Multiple prior examinations, including most recent\r\nprior MRI brain without and with contrast (3.0 Tesla), 9/9/2024.\r\nCT brain without contrast, 11/5/2021.\r\n\r\n\r\nFINDINGS:\r\n\r\n\r\nSome of the imaging series are degraded by motion artifact.\r\nNonetheless, diagnostic information is felt to be obtained.\r\n\r\n\r\nSurgical changes of prior dorsal midline suboccipital craniotomy.\r\nThere are surgical changes of the left greater than right\r\ncerebellar hemispheres and vermis. Small communicating upper\r\ncervical pseudomeningocele is again identified. Again noted are\r\nsurgical changes of prior left parietal craniotomy, with\r\nassociated parietal surgical cavity and peripheral gliosis.\r\n\r\n\r\nStable surgical changes of prior right frontal catheter tracts\r\nwith surrounding encephalomalacia/gliosis.\r\n\r\n\r\nSince prior MRI of 9/9/2024, there is new interval surgical\r\nchange, with evidence for interval resection of previously\r\ndepicted complex cystic appearing lesions abutting the left\r\nsuperior cerebellar peduncle and resection of the left\r\nparasagittal cystic component along the leftward posterolateral\r\nmedulla and pons extending along the left lateral margin of the\r\nfourth ventricle. \r\n\r\n\r\nA previously depicted dorsal midline component along the\r\nposterior margin of the third ventricle projecting into the\r\ndorsal midline midbrain has been largely resected. There is\r\nvariable surrounding FLAIR signal hyperintensity. There is a\r\nsmall residual T2 hyperintense component, which could represent\r\ntiny residual lesion versus CSF measuring up to roughly 1.0 cm\r\n(AP) x 0.3 cm (SI) as measured on image 40 of series 15. \r\n\r\n\r\nThere is otherwise persistent T2/FLAIR hyperintense cystic/solid\r\ncomponents within the left midbrain with some extension of signal\r\nalteration into the superior cerebellar peduncle and pons, and\r\nwithin the left posterior thalamus. The somewhat nodular\r\nappearing left midbrain lesions measure roughly 1.8 cm (AP) x 1.0\r\ncm (TRV), as measured on image 32 of series 9. Comparison to the\r\nprior examination is limited due to the interval surgical\r\nchanges. The dominant lesion within the posterior left thalamus\r\nmeasures 1.0 cm (AP) x 0.9 cm (TRV), as measured on image 30 of\r\nseries 9, and likely slightly smaller in the interim.\r\n\r\n\r\nFollowing contrast administration, there is mild dural\r\nthickening/enhancement along the left cerebral convexity, most\r\nnotably deep to the region of craniotomy, and likely representing\r\npostsurgical/reactive enhancement.\r\n\r\n\r\nThere is enhancement associated with the left posterior thalamic\r\nsignal abnormality, and there is enhancement which extends along\r\nand involves the left superior cerebellar peduncle and\r\ndorsolateral midbrain and upper pons. There is some associated\r\nenhancement and thickening of the left tentorial leaflet.\r\nOtherwise, no suspicious enhancement associated with the\r\nresection site within the posterior fossa communicating with the\r\nfourth ventricle.\r\n\r\n\r\nProminent ex vacuo dilatation of the fourth ventricle, increased\r\nin size in the interim, concerning for an element of possible\r\nventricular entrapment. There is new/increased FLAIR signal\r\nhyperintensity within the parenchyma along the margins of the\r\nfourth ventricle which could represent periventricular\r\ninterstitial edema. The AP dimension of the fourth ventricle\r\nmeasures up to roughly 4.2 cm, and there is new/increased mass\r\neffect upon the brainstem which is ventrally displaced. There is\r\nassociated decrease in extra-axial CSF along the brainstem. \r\nThere is persistent obliteration of the aqueduct of Sylvius.\r\n\r\n\r\nThe mildly prominent third ventricle may be slightly smaller in\r\nsize. Otherwise, lateral ventricles are mildly prominent and\r\nsimilar in size.\r\n\r\n\r\nThere is again prominence of the foramina of Magendie and\r\nLuschka. \r\n\r\n\r\nNo evidence for significant supratentorial midline shift. \r\n\r\n\r\nChronic volume loss of the cerebellum, left greater than right. \r\nPersistent mild thinning of the corpus callosum.\r\n\r\n\r\nThere is again susceptibility with some interval change which may\r\nbe due to interval evolution and/or interval surgery compatible\r\nwith parenchymal hemosiderin staining/chronic blood product\r\nwithin the region of the left hippocampal tail and body/mesial\r\ntemporal lobe.\r\n\r\n\r\nThere is again at least partial encasement of a portion of the\r\nleft basal vein of Rosenthal. The distal left PCA is not well\r\nevaluated. Otherwise, major central intracranial arterial and\r\nsuperficial dural venous sinuses appear patent.\r\n\r\n\r\nMild prominence of the pituitary gland, likely in keeping with\r\npatient's demographics.\r\n\r\n\r\nNo definite abnormality in visualized orbits. \r\n\r\n\r\nBilateral scalp and dorsal midline suboccipital soft tissue\r\nchanges related to prior surgery.\r\n\r\n\r\nMiddle ear cavities and mastoid air cells clear. Trace mucosal\r\nthickening within paranasal sinuses.\r\n\r\n","interpretation":NaN,"note":NaN}},{"resource":{"resourceType":"Observation","id":"fzh.wy6PXQH7hZ8g7Bt-1B32e0PaPrpJCdKSbPuIGAnY4","status":"final","category":"[{id=null, image 79) measuring up to 6 mm in thickening, more noticeable at the roof of the surgical cavity surrounding the left Rosenthal vein, and extending to the posterior aspect of the left mesencephalon (series 8 image 76). \u00a0There is remonstration of abnormal T2 signal centered at the dorsal aspect of the left mesencephalon (series 6 image 18) There is no restricted diffusion in a vascular distribution to suggest acute infarction. \u00a0The ventricles remain prominent, as before.IMPRESSION:There has been gross total resection of the enhancing cystic structures in the posterior fossa. involving the tail of the hippocampus, medial thalamus and medial to the atrium of left lateral ventricle. \u00a0The tumor measures approximately measures approximately 35 x 33 x 43 mm (oblique CC x TRV x AP (series 9 image 16 and series 7 image 54). There is peripheral irregular enhancement seen within the cystic component. \u00a0There is hemorrhage fluid levels present in the cysts. \u00a0A large cyst present at pineal region, has been increased since prior MRI examination dated 08/12/2024. \u00a0It is causing mass effect on the posterior medial aspect of the midbrain and obstruction of the cerebral aqueduct. \u00a0Multiple foci of susceptibility hypointensities are present in this lesion.There is dilatation of the bilateral lateral and 3rd ventricles, unchanged. \u00a0The 4th ventricle is cystically dilated and communicating with midline resection cavity in the cerebellum from prior surgery. \u00a0There is volume loss of left cerebellar hemisphere.There is resection cavity present in the left posterior parietal occipital lobe and tract in the right frontal lobe.There is no extra-axial hemorrhage or midline shift. \u00a0The orbits are normal.There is no sinus mucosal disease. \u00a0There is evidence of left parietal Unchanged\r\npostsurgical ectasia of the fourth ventricle. Prominent foramina\r\nof Magendie and Luschka are unchanged.\r\n\r\n\r\nRedemonstration of cystic and solid mass centered within the left\r\nposterior fossa abutting the left superior cerebellar peduncle\r\nand extending into the left cerebral peduncle and left posterior\r\nthalamus. This lesion measures 41 mm AP x 40 mm TR x 29 mm CC\r\n(series 8, image 34; series 10, image 26), previously 41 mm AP x\r\n40 mm TR x 29 mm CC (series 9, image 35; series 15, image 26).\r\n\r\n\r\nThe fluid-fluid level and T1 shortening within the posterior\r\ninferior cystic component of the lesion has resolved (series 8,\r\nimage 35). This posterior cystic component measures 13 x 11 mm\r\n(series 8, image 35), previously 12 x 10 mm (series 9, image 36).\r\n\r\n\r\nThe left parasagittal cystic component along the left lateral\r\nmargin of the fourth ventricle demonstrates slightly increased\r\nmarginal linear and nodular enhancement compared to 8/12/2024,\r\nalthough this is not significantly changed from 6/24/2024.\r\n\r\n\r\nThe midline cystic component along the posterior margin of the\r\nthird ventricle measures 15 x 19 mm (series 5, image 50),\r\npreviously 14 x 17 mm (series 6, image 48). Persistent\r\nobliteration of the aqueduct of Sylvius is unchanged.\r\n\r\n\r\nStable enhancement pattern within the lesion.\r\n\r\n\r\nStable obstruction and enlargement of the ventricles. Persistent\r\nmild thinning of the corpus callosum.\r\n\r\n\r\nAt least partial encasement of a portion of the left basal vein\r\nof Rosenthal and the distal left PCA is not significantly changed\r\nfrom the prior study. Major intracranial vasculature and dural\r\nvenous sinuses are otherwise patent.\r\n\r\n\r\nChronic volume loss of the cerebellum, left greater than right.\r\n\r\n\r\nNo definite abnormality in visualized orbits. \r\n\r\n\r\nMiddle ear cavities and mastoid air cells clear. Paranasal\r\nsinuses _display=null}","effectiveDateTime":"2024-08-12T14:35:52Z","valueQuantity":NaN,"valueString":"MRI BRAIN WITHOUT AND WITH CONTRAST.\r\n\r\n\r\nCLINICAL INDICATION: \r\nMidbrain low-grade glioma\r\nGlioma, growth\r\nDx: Pilocytic astrocytoma of cerebellum [C71.6 (ICD-10-CM)]\r\n\r\n\r\nTECHNIQUE: \r\nSagittal T1 MPRAGE with axial reformations, axial and sagittal\r\nTSE T2, axial and coronal FLAIR, axial SE T1, axial SWI,\r\npost-contrast T1 sagittal MPRAGE with axial and coronal\r\nreformations, axial SE T1 post-contrast ASL and axial\r\ndiffusion-weighted imaging were performed on a 3.0 Tesla system.\r\n\r\n\r\nCOMPARISON: \r\nComparison is made to multiple prior studies dating back to MRI\r\nof the brain without and with contrast dated May 27, 2018 (3.0\r\nTesla magnet), with comparison to most recently performed MRI of\r\nthe brain without and with contrast dated June 24, 2024 (3.0\r\nTesla magnet).\r\n\r\n\r\nFINDINGS:\r\n\r\n\r\nPostsurgical changes with right transfrontal shunt track, left\r\nsuboccipital craniotomy with postsurgical changes within the\r\nposterior fossa extending to the craniocervical junction (with\r\nunchanged small communicating suboccipital/upper cervical\r\npseudomeningocele), and left parietal craniotomy with\r\nencephalomalacia within the left parietal lobe. Postsurgical\r\nectasia of the fourth ventricle is again noted. There is\r\nprominence of the outlet foramina of Magendie and Luschka,\r\nunchanged from multiple prior examinations.\r\n\r\n\r\nThe cystic and solid mass is centered within the left posterior\r\nfossa abutting the left superior cerebellar peduncle and extends\r\ninto the left cerebral peduncle and left posterior thalamus. \r\nIn the interim, there has been progression of fluid\r\nfluid/possible blood fluid levels within the posterior inferior\r\ncystic component of the lesion, best appreciated on axial FLAIR,\r\nseries 9, images 34-38 in comparison to immediate prior FLAIR\r\naxial series 9 images 34-36. There is concurrent appearance of\r\nnew T1 shortening, more so along the anterior aspect of the fluid\r\nlevel, again suggestive of blood products, and confirmed on SWI\r\nimaging.\r\nThis posterior cystic component now measures approximately 12.9\r\nmm in transverse dimension by 10 mm in AP dimension as measured\r\noff of axial FLAIR, series 9, image 36, in comparison to prior\r\nstudy and is similar level on the same sequence, measuring\r\napproximately 11.7 mm in transverse dimension by 8.3 mm in AP\r\ndimension, on axial FLAIR, series 9, image 35, slightly increased\r\nin the interim.\r\nIn the region of this eccentric left parasagittal cystic\r\ncomponent of the tumor, extending from approximately the 3:00\r\nposition inferiorly along the left lateral margin of the fourth\r\nventricle and superiorly to the left incisional region, there is\r\nfairly robust rim enhancement, which appears to be slightly more\r\nsolid along its superior margin. Again is is not significantly\r\nchanged from immediate prior examination, but definitively\r\nsmaller than on more remote MRI dated March 15, 2022, best\r\nappreciated on axial MPRAGE postcontrast imaging.\r\nWhilst the overall size of the tumor has not significantly\r\ndifferent from immediate prior examination, there is definitive\r\ndecrease in size of the lesion in comparison to more remote\r\nstudies dating back to March 15, 2022, and definitively smaller\r\nthan on original MRI presentation from May 27, 2018.\r\n\r\n\r\nHowever, the midline cystic lesion emanating from the tectal\r\nregion along the posterior margin of the third ventricle, leading\r\nto obliteration of the aqueduct of Sylvius, has progressively\r\nincreased over time, whilst not significantly changed from\r\nimmediate prior MRI of June 24, 2024, has definitively grown in\r\ncomparison to the immediate study prior to that study on April\r\n30, 2024.\r\nOn today's examination, it currently measures approximately 15.8\r\nmm in AP dimension by 13.0 mm in transverse dimension, likely not\r\nsignificantly changed allowing for differences in angulation and\r\nmeasurement technique, (previously measuring 1.8 x 1.4 cm).\r\nThis is again noted to result in ventricular obstruction with no\r\nsignificant interval change in size of lateral and third\r\nventricles. \r\nT2 hypointense flow jet through the endoscopic third\r\nventriculostomy defect is again visualized.\r\n\r\n\r\nHemosiderin is noted lining the left occipital horn region,\r\nstanding the bilateral choroid plexus, with focal\r\nhemosiderin/narrowing seen within the temporal horn of the right\r\nlateral ventricle. There is corresponding calcifications\r\ndocumented on most recent CT head dated November 05, 2021.\r\n\r\n\r\nThe corpus callosum is mildly thinned and slightly tented\r\nupwards, unchanged from prior examination.\r\n\r\n\r\nThe tumor is again noted to at least partially encase a segment\r\nof the left basal vein of Rosenthal and distal left PCA. Major\r\ncentral intracranial arterial vasculature and superficial dural\r\nvenous sinuses are otherwise patent.\r\n\r\n\r\nPersistent chronic volume loss of the left greater than right\r\ncerebellar hemispheres. \r\n\r\n\r\nNo definite abnormality is seen in the visualized portions of the\r\norbits.\r\n\r\n\r\nSuggestion of trace fluid within the left mastoid. The right\r\nmastoid and middle ear cavities are clear. Few areas of trace\r\nmucosal thickening within the paranasal sinuses.  \r\nPersistent leftward bowing of the nasal septum, with associated\r\nprominent leftward projecting nasal septal spur narrowing the\r\nleft nasal passage.\r\n\r\n","interpretation":NaN,"note":NaN}},{"resource":{"resourceType":"Observation","id":"fQvr2SAWXD13.lg2TSOuPFA4","status":"final","category":"[{id=null, extension=null, coding=[{id=null, extension=null, system=http://terminology.hl7.org/CodeSystem/observation-category, _system=null, version=null, _version=null, code=imaging, _code=null, display=Imaging, _display=null, userSelected=null, _userSelected=null}], text=Imaging, _text=null}, {id=null, extension=null, coding=[{id=null, extension=null, system=urn:oid:1.2.840.114350.1.13.20.2.7.10.798268.30, _system=null, version=null, _version=null, code=Imaging, _code=null, display=Imaging, _display=null, userSelected=null, _userSelected=null}], text=Imaging, _text=null}]","code":"{id=null, extension=null, coding=null, text=Impression, _text=null}","subject":"{id=null, extension=null, reference=Patient/e4BwD8ZYDBccepXcJ.Ilo3w3, _reference=null, type=null, _type=null, identifier=null, display=Massari, Abigail, _display=null}","effectiveDateTime":"2024-08-12T14:35:52Z","valueQuantity":NaN,"valueString":"\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n1. WITH CONTRAST.\r\n\r\n\r\nCLINICAL INDICATION: Midbrain low-grade glioma\r\n\r\n\r\nTECHNIQUE: Multiplanar multisequence MRI of the brain was\r\nperformed prior to and following intravenous contrast on a 3\r\nTesla scanner.\r\n\r\n\r\nCOMPARISON: MRI brain 4/30/2024, 1/23/2024, 11/1/2023 \r\n\r\n\r\nFINDINGS:\r\n\r\n\r\nPostsurgical changes with right transfrontal shunt track, left\r\nsuboccipital craniotomy with postsurgical changes within the\r\nposterior fossa extending to the craniocervical junction (with\r\nunchanged small communicating suboccipital/upper cervical\r\npseudomeningocele), and left parietal craniotomy with\r\nencephalomalacia within the left parietal lobe.\r\n\r\n\r\nThe cystic and solid mass is centered within the left posterior\r\nfossa abutting the left superior cerebellar peduncle and extends\r\ninto the left cerebral peduncle and left posterior thalamus.\r\nRim-enhancing portion of the lesion abutting the left superior\r\ncerebellar peduncle is increased in size as compared to prior\r\nmeasuring 2.2 x 1.8 cm, prior on 4/30/2024 2.2 x 1.4 cm. There is\r\nalso a significant increase in size of a cystic lesion with mass\r\neffect and obstruction of the aqueduct of Sylvius, currently\r\nmeasuring 1.8 x 1.4 cm (prior 0.9 x 0.8 cm). This results in\r\nventricular obstruction with interval increase in size of lateral\r\nand third ventricles. T2 hypointense flow jet through the\r\nendoscopic third ventriculostomy defect is again visualized.\r\n\r\n\r\nThe corpus callosum is mildly thinned and slightly tented\r\nupwards, unchanged from prior examination.\r\n\r\n\r\nThe tumor is again noted to at least partially encase a segment\r\nof the left basal vein of Rosenthal and distal left PCA. Major\r\ncentral intracranial arterial vasculature and superficial dural\r\nvenous sinuses are otherwise patent.\r\n\r\n\r\nPersistent chronic volume loss of the left greater than right\r\ncerebellar hemispheres. \r\n\r\n\r\nNo definite abnormality is seen in the visualized portions of the\r\norbits.\r\n\r\n\r\nSuggestion of trace fluid within the left mastoid. The right\r\nmastoid and middle ear cavities are clear. Few areas of trace\r\nmucosal thickening within the paranasal sinuses. Abigail, _display=null}","effectiveDateTime":"2024-04-30T23:47:00Z","valueQuantity":NaN,"valueString":"MRI CERVICAL, THORACIC, AND LUMBAR SPINE, WITH  CONTRAST:\r\n\r\n\r\nCLINICAL INDICATION: midbrain low grade glioma with h/o T-spine\r\nmetastatic disease.  Follow up for interval change.\r\n\r\n\r\nTECHNIQUE: Multiplanar multisequence MRI of the spine was\r\nperformed following intravenous contrast on a 1.5 Tesla scanner.\r\n\r\n\r\nCOMPARISON: Recent prior spine MRI from September 13, 2022 on a 3\r\nTesla scanner and August 4, 2021 on 1.5 Tesla scanner.\r\n\r\n\r\nFINDINGS:\r\n\r\n\r\nRedemonstrated are changes of suboccipital craniotomy and\r\nresection of the posterior arch of C1, with an associated\r\npseudomeningocele slightly smaller than the prior MRI. \r\n\r\n\r\nNo pathological contrast enhancement detected within the\r\nintradural space. Linear dural enhancement along the surgical\r\ncavity, expected.\r\n\r\n\r\nSerpiginous tiny areas of enhancement surrounding the cord,\r\nlikely vascular in origin. There are no enhancing nodular lesions\r\nwithin the intradural space.\r\n\r\n\r\nElongated dens, normal variant. Again noted is stable reversal of\r\nthe normal cervical lordosis. \r\nAgain noted right-sided deviation of the lumbar spine, likely\r\npostural.\r\n\r\n\r\nAgain noted is stable extensive/diffuse dural ectasia below the\r\nlevel of C7. \r\n\r\n\r\nThe remainder of the vertebral bodies maintain their height,\r\nagain with only 4 lumbar type vertebral bodies noted. Vertebral\r\ndisc desiccation and small disc bulges from C2-3 to C5-6 levels\r\nwithout any associated nerve root compression.\r\n\r\n\r\nThe previously noted T2 linear low signal intensity is evident in\r\nthe expected location of the central canal at C7 and T1, is not\r\nwell seen on today's study. The remainder of the spinal cord is\r\nnormal in size and signal.\r\n\r\n\r\nThe conus medullaris is normal in shape and terminates at the\r\nlower L1 level.\r\n\r\n\r\nStable tiny fatty infiltration along the filum terminale.\r\n\r\n\r\nLumbar and sacral perineural root sleeve cysts are again noted\r\nand unchanged in appearance.\r\n\r\n\r\nThe kidneys are orthotopic without hydronephrosis. \r\n\r\n\r\nBilateral extrarenal pelves are noted, similar to prior study.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n","interpretation":NaN,"note":NaN}},{"resource":{"resourceType":"Observation","id":"fs5kbBK0vqFT4R4CvJWYOPQ4","status":"final","category":"[{id=null, extension=null, coding=[{id=null, extension=null, system=http://terminology.hl7.org/CodeSystem/observation-category, _system=null, version=null, _version=null, code=imaging, _code=null, display=Imaging, _display=null, userSelected=null, _userSelected=null}], text=Imaging, _text=null}, {id=null, extension=null, coding=[{id=null, extension=null, system=urn:oid:1.2.840.114350.1.13.20.2.7.10.798268.30, _system=null, version=null, _version=null, code=Imaging, _code=null, display=Imaging, _display=null, userSelected=null, _userSelected=null}], text=Imaging, _text=null}]","code":"{id=null, extension=null, coding=null, text=Impression, _text=null}","subject":"{id=null, extension=null, reference=Patient/e4BwD8ZYDBccepXcJ.Ilo3w3, _reference=null, type=null, _type=null, identifier=null, display=Massari, Abigail, _display=null}","effectiveDateTime":"2024-04-30T22:57:00Z","valueQuantity":NaN,"valueString":"\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n1. Compared to MRI from January 2024 there is overall similar\r\nsize and morphology of the known tumor centered in the left\r\nmidbrain, as detailed, except for widening of a focal posterior\r\ncomponent.  Decreased conspicuity of FLAIR signal in some of the\r\nlocules is attribute it to technical differences of the study\r\nbeing performed on 1.5 Tesla compared to prior study on 3 Tesla\r\nscanner.\r\n\r\n\r\n2. Stable size and configuration of the ventricular system again\r\nnoting a prominent dilatation of the fourth ventricle. MRI\r\nfindings reflecting patency of the third ventriculostomy. \r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nRequires Act 112 notification: False\r\nAct 112^False","interpretation":NaN,"note":NaN}},{"resource":{"resourceType":"Observation","id":"fbtNiXSH6KoxgC1wBT9chUA4","status":"final","category":"[{id=null, extension=null, coding=[{id=null, extension=null, system=http://terminology.hl7.org/CodeSystem/observation-category, _system=null, version=null, _version=null, code=imaging, _code=null, display=Imaging, _display=null, userSelected=null, _userSelected=null}], text=Imaging, _text=null}, {id=null, extension=null, coding=[{id=null, extension=null, system=urn:oid:1.2.840.114350.1.13.20.2.7.10.798268.30, _system=null, version=null, _version=null, code=Imaging, _code=null, display=Imaging, _display=null, userSelected=null, _userSelected=null}], text=Imaging, _text=null}]","code":"{id=null, extension=null, coding=null, text=Narrative, _text=null}","subject":"{id=null, extension=null, reference=Patient/e4BwD8ZYDBccepXcJ.Ilo3w3, _reference=null, type=null, _type=null, identifier=null, display=Massari, Abigail, _display=null}","effectiveDateTime":"2024-04-30T22:57:00Z","valueQuantity":NaN,"valueString":"MRI BRAIN WITHOUT AND WITH CONTRAST.\r\n\r\n\r\nCLINICAL INDICATION: Midbrain low-grade glioma, follow-up study\r\nfor interval change.\r\nPer electronic medical record, 18-year-old with recurrent\r\nmidbrain, low-grade glioma, follow-up on targeted (selumetinib)\r\ntherapy. \r\n\r\n\r\nTECHNIQUE: Multiplanar multisequence MRI of the brain was\r\nperformed prior to and following intravenous contrast on a 1.5\r\nTesla scanner.\r\n\r\n\r\nCOMPARISON: Most recent prior MRI January 23, 2024 on 3 Tesla\r\nscanner and multiple prior studies\r\n\r\n\r\nFINDINGS:\r\n\r\n\r\nAgain noted are the right superior frontal approach\r\ninstrumentation tracts with gliosis/encephalomalacia along their\r\ncourse. Postoperative changes along left parietal instrumentation\r\ntract without interval change. Additional postoperative changes\r\nare apparent from prior suboccipital craniotomy/resection of\r\nposterior arch of C1 and posterior fossa tumor resection, with a\r\nsmall communicating suboccipital/upper cervical pseudomeningocele\r\npresent, minimally smaller from prior examination.\r\n\r\n\r\nThere is a markedly heterogeneous signal intensity mass lesion\r\nconsistent with the known tumor involving the left dorsal\r\nmidbrain, left superior cerebellar peduncle, posterior left\r\nthalamus, anterior/superior left cerebellum, and adjacent left\r\nmedial occipitotemporal junction region of the brain. There are\r\nmultiple cystic and solid appearing components, with dependent\r\nlevels within some of the cystic components, and some of the\r\nareas are hemosiderin stained likely from prior surgical effect.\r\n\r\n\r\nOverall size of the multiple components of the tumor have not\r\nsignificantly changed except for a prominent posterior enhancing\r\ncomponent, which demonstrates an increased internal nonenhancing\r\ncystic component measuring approximately 2.1 x 1.6 cm (AP by\r\ntransverse) as measured on series 17 image 20, compared to prior\r\nmeasurement of 2.1 x 1.4 cm when measured in a similar fashion.\r\nThere is decreased FLAIR hyperintensity in several locules on\r\ntoday's study, which is attribute it to the present study on 1.5\r\nTesla scanner compared to prior study on 3 Tesla scanner. Stable\r\nlocal mass effect. \r\n\r\n\r\nSimilar prominence of the ventricular system, including\r\ndilatation of the lateral and third ventricles, and similar\r\ndilatation/ex vacuo dilatation and deformity of the fourth\r\nventricle. Again the cerebral aqueduct appears completely\r\neffaced. \r\n\r\n\r\nT2 hypointense flow jet is identified through the endoscopic\r\nthird ventriculostomy defect, indicating patency. There is stable\r\nwidening of the foramina of Luschka, with lack of CSF pulsation\r\nthroughout dilated fourth ventricle and foramina of Luschka. \r\nSimilar FLAIR signal hyperintensity, along the posterolateral\r\nfourth ventricle, likely representing surgical related gliosis.\r\n\r\n\r\nMultiple areas of susceptibility artifact are present, within the\r\nposterior fossa and upper cervical cord/cervicomedullary\r\njunction, left parieto-occipital and mesial temporal lobe\r\nregions, left lateral ventricle, as well as within the right\r\nlateral ventricle , most notably anterior temporal horn, are\r\nbetter visualized on the SWI images on the prior study. Majority\r\nof these areas represent chronic hemorrhage/hemosiderin\r\ndeposition, some represent calcification, including the focus in\r\nthe right anterior temporal horn, as depicted on CT of 11/5/2021.\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\n\r\nThe corpus callosum is mildly thinned and slightly tented\r\nupwards, unchanged from prior examination.\r\n\r\n\r\nThe tumor is again noted to at least partially encase a segment\r\nof the left basal vein of Rosenthal and distal left PCA. Major\r\ncentral intracranial arterial vasculature and superficial dural\r\nvenous sinuses are otherwise patent.\r\n\r\n\r\nPersistent chronic volume loss of the left greater than right\r\ncerebellar hemispheres. Diffuse mild supratentorial sulcal\r\nprominence is again evident. \r\n\r\n\r\nThe corpus callosum is mildly thinned and slightly tented\r\nupwards, unchanged from prior examination. \r\n\r\n\r\nNo definite abnormality is seen in the visualized portions of the\r\norbits.\r\n\r\n\r\nSuggestion of trace fluid within the left mastoid. The right\r\nmastoid and middle ear cavities are clear. Few areas of trace\r\nmucosal thickening within the paranasal sinuses. Persistent\r\nleftward bowing of the nasal septum, with associated prominent\r\nleftward projecting nasal septal spur narrowing the left nasal\r\npassage.\r\n\r\n","interpretation":NaN,"note":NaN}},{"resource":{"resourceType":"Observation","id":"frvOzVzuYQRgwKbv71D0JBg4","status":"final","category":"[{id=null, extension=null, SURG. DATE:  03/16/2021
TIME OF PROCEDURE:  02:15 PM
SURGEON:  Alexander Tucker, MD
ASSISTANT:  Peter J Madsen, MD and Phillip Storm, MD.
Please note, Dr. Madsen assisted with this procedure as no qualified resident was available.
PREOPERATIVE DIAGNOSES:
Hydrocephalus.
4th ventricular outlet obstruction.
Pilocytic astrocytoma.
POSTOPERATIVE DIAGNOSES:
Hydrocephalus.
4th ventricular outlet obstruction.
Pilocytic astrocytoma.
PROCEDURES PERFORMED:
Suboccipital craniotomy for 4th ventricular fenestration.
C1 laminectomy.
Endoscopic 3rd ventriculostomy.
Placement of external ventricular drain.
ESTIMATED BLOOD LOSS:  20 cc.
ANESTHESIA:  General endotracheal.
DRAINS:  External ventricular drain x1.
COMPLICATIONS:  None.
FINDINGS:  Scar surrounding the outlet of the 4th ventricle and intact tuber cinereum.
SPECIMEN:  None.
INDICATION FOR THE PROCEDURE:  The patient is a 15-year-old female with a history of pilocytic astrocytoma, who recently underwent a craniotomy for tumor reresection.  Postoperatively, the patient required placement of a right frontal external ventricular drain.  Since that time, the patient has had a change in mental status.  Repeat neuroimaging revealed enlargement of the 4th ventricle.  Given the patient's symptoms and radiographic findings, it was determined that she would benefit from surgical intervention.
CONSENT:  The patient's family was consented for the procedure.  The indications, benefits, risks, and potential complications of the procedure were discussed with the patient's family in detail.  Discussed risks of the procedure include, but not limited to, worsening of the current status, possible need for further procedures, risk of infection, headaches, CSF leak, seizures, injury to major vessels causing hemorrhage, stroke, coma, and even death.  The patient's family understood these risks and elected to proceed with the operation.
DESCRIPTION OF PROCEDURE:  The patient was brought to the operating suite and was intubated and sedated by the Anesthesia Service.  The patient was placed into a Mayfield head holder and turned prone onto the operating table with her body supported on gel rolls.  The neck was gently flexed and the Mayfield head holder was attached to the operating table.  The patient was given preoperative prophylactic IV antibiotics.  The eyes were taped shut to prevent corneal abrasion.  All pressure points were carefully padded.  The hair was clipped over the area of the planned incision.  A Bair Hugger was placed to maintain control of core body temperature.  The patient was prepped and draped in the standard sterile fashion.  A comprehensive surgical time-out was performed.  The skin was opened sharply with a #15 blade scalpel by Dr. Madsen.  Bovie electrocautery was used to dissect the subcutaneous tissue.  Self-retaining retractors were placed in the wound.  Dissection continued until the suboccipital bone and the posterior arch of C1 were exposed entirely.  Using a Leksell rongeur, a C1 laminectomy was performed by Dr. Madsen.  Using Kerrison rongeur, the bone edges were smoothed and the laminectomy widened.  Next, a single midline bur hole was placed with a handheld drill right along the keel by Dr. Madsen.  Using Kerrison rongeur, the craniectomy was extended into the foramen magnum.  The underlying dura was thinned.  Using a tenting suture and 11 blade, Dr. Madsen opened the dura.  The durotomy was continued superiorly and inferiorly down to the C1 laminectomy defect.  Dural edges were tented back and the cerebellar tonsils were clearly visible underneath a layer of scarred arachnoid.  The arachnoid was then opened sharply with micro scissors and CSF under pressure was appreciated.  Next, the left cerebellar tonsil was partially resected and the 4th ventricle was entered.  This fenestration was then widened until there was free communication of CSF between the spinal subarachnoid space and the 4th ventricle.  Hemostasis was achieved.  The wound was copiously irrigated.  The dura was then closed primarily with 4-0 Nurolon suture.  DuraGen was placed over the dural closure.  Epidural hemostasis was achieved.  The cervical musculature was closed with 0 Vicryl suture.  The craniocervical fascia was closed with 0 Vicryl suture.  The dermis reapproximated with 2-0 Vicryl suture and finally, the skin was closed with 4-0 Monocryl.  The drapes were removed and the patient was then repositioned supine.  The patient was then re-prepped and draped in the standard sterile fashion.  The patient's previous external ventricular drain wound site was reopened.  The external ventricular drain was removed and discarded.  Next, the endoscope was brought to the operative field.  The irrigation connected, the lens attached and focused and the camera was white balanced.  Next, following the path of the previous external ventricular drain, the scope was advanced into the right lateral ventricle by Dr. Madsen.  Next, the camera was driven into the 3rd ventricle and the mamillary bodies, tuber cinereum and infundibular recess were all appreciated.  The floor of the 3rd ventricle was examined and no stoma was visible.  Dr. Madsen then drove the camera to an appropriate location.  A blunt tipped probe was then passed through the floor of the 3rd ventricle.  A 3-French Fogarty balloon was then placed into the hole and inflated.  This process was repeated with a 4-French Fogarty balloon, a small bubble of air was appreciated coming through the floor of the 3rd ventricle.  The camera was then driven through the fenestration by Dr. Madsen and the basilar artery and clival dura were clearly seen.  Finally, the camera was withdrawn.  A new Bactiseal external ventricular drain catheter was then passed down the tract into the ventricle.  This was tunneled out of the scalp, trimmed to the level of the skin, reattached with a steel straight connector and secured with 2-0 silk ties.  The drain was then anchored to the scalp with a 0 silk stitch.  The area surrounding the bur hole was packed with Gelfoam.  Hemostasis was achieved. POSTOPERATIVE DIAGNOSIS:  Pilocytic astrocytoma.
PROCEDURE:  Left parieto-occipital craniotomy for tumor with navigation, vycor retractor and neuromonitoring and placement of an antibiotic impregnated ventricular drain.
INDICATIONS:  The patient is a 15-year-old girl who underwent a craniotomy for a large posterior fossa tumor.  She had significant posterior fossa syndrome and has made a remarkable recovery.  We had a discussion about approaches.  The decision was made to go from above rather than a supracerbellar, infratentorial approach as the tumor had been relatively stable in the infratentorial component, and it was a cyst that was growing. Further, I did not feel that we could get a gross total resection from 1 approach alone and she had not been on a MEK inhibitor, so we elected to go from above using a Vycor retractor and navigation.  No qualified resident was available; therefore, Dr. Tucker assisted.
DESCRIPTION OF PROCEDURE:  Once in the operating room IV access was obtained.  General anesthesia was induced.  Antibiotics were given.  Dr. Tucker placed her in the Mayfield head holder and registered the navigation system.  I confirmed its accuracy.  Dr. Tucker then sterilely prepped and draped the patient in the usual fashion.  Time-out was taken prior to skin incision.  A 15 blade knife was used by Dr. Tucker to make a linear incision.  I used Bovie for hemostasis.  Raney clips were used and a retractor was placed to expose the skull.  Dr. Tucker placed 1 burr hole.  I used the Penfield 3 to free the dura and protect the skin as Dr. Tucker took the craniotome to perform the craniotomy.  I put a 4 Nurolon stitch in the dura to tent it up.  Dr. Tucker opened with an 11 blade knife and I inspected the brain under the dura and Dr. Tucker opened with a Metzenbaum scissor.  I used the navigation to map out the entry point as Dr. Tucker took a strip with irrigation, placed it over the brain to do motor mapping.  We were all in phase.  Dr. Tucker advanced it more anteriorly and we did begin to see some phase reversal, confirming what we believed by anatomy and navigation that we were well behind the motor strip and not near Wernicke area.  Dr. Tucker used the bipolar to coagulate the cortex.  I used micro scissors to open and then using the Vycor retractor, I gently advanced the retractors.  Dr. Tucker used navigation as we would intermittently check as we advanced the Vycor retractor.  Once we felt we were close to the ventricle, we removed the internal portion of the Vycor.  Using gentle suction, I entered the ventricle and repositioned the retractor so that I could see the cyst.  Dr. Tucker then held the retractor as I used the bipolar and scissors to open the cyst and remove the outer portions.  We then were able to see tumor.  Using gentle suction began removing tumor and taking biopsies.  We knew the basal vein of Rosenthal as well as the posterior cerebral arteries were passing through the tumor.  So as Dr. Tucker confirmed with navigation and directed the Vycor retractor, I took multiple small biopsies as to not grab a vessel and gentle aspiration.  There was a lot of bleeding during the case as the tumor was friable and quite vascular.  I continued working inferiorly to both gross inspection and confirmation with the navigation that we were getting closer to the large vessels that we had removed most of the, if not all the enhancing tumor above the vasculature.  I then held retractors.  Dr. Tucker copiously irrigated and aspirated.  We both looked around a final time.  I removed the retractor and Dr. Tucker placed the ventricular catheter into the ventricle. Drs. Tucker and Madsen plated the skull with resorbable plates and screws.  I began closing the dura with 4-0 Nurolon.  Then, Dr. Tucker closed the remaining portion on his side.  We laid a piece of DuraGen over top.  I held the skull flap in place while Dr. Tucker and Dr. Madsen secured it to the skull.  We then closed the scalp in layers with absorbable suture.  The patient was extubated.  Ventriculostomy was placed and tunneled out prior to closing the dura, secured with a metal connector, 2-0 silk ties and 0 silk stitch.  The patient was extubated and taken to the ICU.  I was present for and participated in the critical portions of the case.

PROCEDURE PERFORMED:  Right frontal bur hole for external ventricular drain placement with stereotactic guidance.
INDICATIONS FOR SURGERY:  Abigail is a 15-year-old girl who underwent tumor resection 4 days prior to the present surgery.  Her EVD stopped working, presumably due to blood around the catheter.  She became very symptomatic with headache, vomiting, lethargy, and risks, benefits, and alternatives of placement of a new right frontal drain were discussed with the patient's parents, and informed signed consent was obtained.  She had a trapped 4th ventricle, apparently, on CAT scan, but it was possible that this was in communication with the rest of the ventricles.  Nevertheless, with larger ventricles and a nonfunctioning drain and new-onset symptoms, the 1st step was an EVD.
PROCEDURE DESCRIPTION:  She was brought to the operating room, and general endotracheal anesthesia was induced.  Appropriate lines were placed.  The bed was turned.  She was registered with stereotactic navigation system, prepped and draped in usual sterile fashion.  A time-out was performed.
A 15 blade was used to make an incision in her old incision that had been used for an EVD in the past.  A self-retaining retractor was placed.  A bur hole was made with a twist drill.  Dura was cauterized and opened with an 11 blade, and using stereotactic guidance, the antibiotic-impregnated catheter was passed into the right lateral ventricle.  CSF returned was a bit xanthochromic and was at relatively low pressure.  The drain was tunneled and secured posteriorly at the skin edge and connected to a sterile CSF collection system.  The wound was irrigated and closed in multilayered fashion with absorbable suture.  She was extubated in the operating room, in good neurologic condition, and brought to the PICU.  There were no complications.  She tolerated the procedure well, and I, the attending neurosurgeon, was present for all critical portions of the case.  All counts were correct at the end of the case.

PREOPERATIVE DIAGNOSIS:  Posterior fossa tumor.
POSTOPERATIVE DIAGNOSIS:  Posterior fossa tumor.
PROCEDURES:
Endoscopic third ventriculostomy with an antibiotic-impregnated ventricular catheter placed with navigation.
Suboccipital craniotomy for tumor resection and navigation.
INDICATIONS FOR PROCEDURE:  Patient is a 13-year-old who was having morning headaches and ultimately underwent an MRI which showed a posterior fossa lesion.  Differential was brainstem exophytic tumor or possible ependymoma.  She was brought to the operating room for diversion of CSF and removal or debulking of the tumor, depending on planes.
DESCRIPTION OF PROCEDURE:  Once in the operating room, IV access was obtained.  General anesthesia was induced.  IV antibiotics were given.  The navigation system was registered using the AxiEM system.  She was then sterilely prepped and draped in the usual fashion.  Time-out was taken prior to skin incision.  15-blade knife was used to make a linear incision.  Bur hole was placed at the coronal suture.  Using the navigation, the antibiotic-impregnated ventricular catheter was inserted.  CSF was collected.  The catheter was then removed, and the endoscope was then inserted, following the ventricular catheter tract.  Once in the lateral ventricle, we made a small hole in the floor of the 3rd ventricle.  It was then ballooned with a Fogarty catheter.  We had a good view of the basilar artery.  We then removed the endoscope.  Ventricular catheter was inserted down the tract and tunneled out and anchored with a metal connector and a 0 silk stitch.  Incision was then closed in layers with absorbable suture.  Patient was then placed in the Mayfield head holder and flipped into prone position.  The optical navigation was then registered.  She was sterilely prepped and draped in the usual fashion.  The neuromonitoring had inserted all the needles prior to flipping.  Time-out was taken again before skin incision.  Incision was made from the inion down to C2.  Bovie was used to expose the skull.  A craniotomy was performed.  A C1 laminectomy was not performed.  The dura was opened, the cerebellar tonsils were spread, and the tumor was seen in the floor of the 4th ventricle.  It was easily elevated for approximately a centimeter and then was clearly seen coming out of the brainstem.  The lesion was coming out from the left but had significantly rotated over to the right, displacing the floor of the 4th over to the right and the aqueduct.  Multiple biopsies were sent which were consistent with a low-grade glial tumor, most consistent with a pilocytic astrocytoma.  Continued debulking the lesion and following it out laterally, where there was a good plane posteriorly and laterally coming around towards but trying to stay out of the middle cerebral peduncle and out the foramen of Luschka.  Continued then debulking superiorly, always keeping track of the floor of the 4th ventricle.  We then found the aqueduct.  A cotton ball was placed in the aqueduct, and a cottonoid was placed in the floor of the 4th ventricle throughout the entire case.  The tumor was seen to tent, and with gentle manipulation, we were able to debulk tumor there.  As we were getting close to the aqueduct and laterally, decision was made not to be overly aggressive as we were getting towards the tegmentum and the roof of the aqueduct.  Confirmed all the areas again with the navigation.  Neuromonitoring signals were stable throughout, without any change.  Meticulous hemostasis was achieved.  The dura was closed with 4-0 Nurolon and DuraGen placed over top, the bone replaced with resorbable plates and screws.  Incision was closed in layers with absorbable suture.  Patient was left intubated and went to MRI.  MRI looked similar to what was expected from the intraoperative resection, as well as confirmed by the intraoperative MRI.  Patient was then taken to the PICU and extubated.  We will follow her for cerebellar mutism, which I had a long discussion with the family afterwards, as we did have to divide portions of the inferior vermis, but that I would not expect weakness postoperatively.  I was present for and participated in the critical portions of the case.
